isHeldByCurrentThread() is a specialized boolean method in the ReentrantLock class. It tells you one simple thing: "Do I (the thread currently running this line of code) own this lock right now?"
It returns true if the current thread holds the lock, and false if the lock is either free or held by a different thread.
1. The Real-World Analogy: Checking Your Pocket
Imagine you are walking through a building with many locked doors.
 * isLocked(): Checks if the door is shut and bolted (anyone could be inside).
 * isHeldByCurrentThread(): You reach into your pocket to see if you are the one holding the key to that specific door.
2. Why is this different from lock.getHoldCount() > 0?
While they are related, they serve different purposes:
 * getHoldCount(): Tells you how many times you locked it (1, 2, 3...).
 * isHeldByCurrentThread(): Is a quick Yes/No safety check. It is often used in assert statements to prevent bugs.
3. Top 3 Use Cases
A. The "Safety Guard" (Assertions)
This is the most common professional use. If you have a method that is not thread-safe and requires a lock to be held before it is called, you can add a check. This catches bugs during development before they hit production.
public void updateSalesforceInternal() {
    // If the developer forgot to lock before calling this, fail immediately!
    if (!lock.isHeldByCurrentThread()) {
        throw new IllegalMonitorStateException("Design Error: You must hold the lock!");
    }
    // Safe to perform logic here...
}

B. Conditional Unlocking
Sometimes, in complex logic with many if/else branches, you might not be 100% sure if a specific path actually acquired the lock. To avoid an IllegalMonitorStateException (which happens if you try to unlock something you don't own), you can check first.
try {
    // complex logic...
} finally {
    if (lock.isHeldByCurrentThread()) {
        lock.unlock();
    }
}

C. Avoiding Deadlocks in Recursive Logic
If you are about to call a method that might block, you can check if you already own the lock. If you do, you know you can proceed without waiting.
4. Comparison: Knowledge is Power
| Method | Returns | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| isLocked() | boolean | Is anyone holding this lock? |
| isHeldByCurrentThread() | boolean | Is the current thread holding this lock? |
| getHoldCount() | int | How many times has the current thread locked it? |
Summary for your Orchestrator
In your Salesforce project, you would use isHeldByCurrentThread() mostly for logging and debugging. If a batch fails, you can log whether the thread still had the lock at the moment of failure, which helps you track down "leakage" where locks aren't being released properly.
